{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/vertigo/background-information/prevalence/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"d4691641-4de6-57f1-a02a-a9d5537caa0d","slug":"prevalence","fullItemName":"Prevalence","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field be386562-53c4-4e4f-a588-3f31aaa6e59e --><h2>How common is it?</h2><!-- end field be386562-53c4-4e4f-a588-3f31aaa6e59e -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item b9e1a3e3-35f4-4aea-932c-1189078c9fbf --><!-- begin field ff29e175-6e8b-4cee-ba86-262d52d45901 --><ul><li><strong>Most balance problems that present in primary care are not true rotatory vertigo.</strong><ul><li>A review of five studies showed that, of people presenting with symptoms of dizziness in the community, around a third were found to have vertigo, this proportion increasing with age [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vertigo/references/\">Hanley et al, 2001</a>].</li><li>In a community study of more than 2000 randomly sampled adults, 7% had reported true vertigo in the previous year [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vertigo/references/\">Yardley et al, 1998</a>].  </li><li>A systematic review of 20 studies of the epidemiology of balance symptoms and disorders in the community estimated the lifetime prevalence of vertigo to be 3–10% [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vertigo/references/\">Murdin and Schilder, 2015</a>].  </li><li>A full-time general practitioner is likely to see 10–20 people with vertigo in 1 year [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vertigo/references/\">Barraclough and Bronstein, 2009</a>]. A German study found that, in a year, around 1% of adults attend for medical assessment with new onset vertigo [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vertigo/references/\">Neuhauser, 2016</a>].  </li></ul></li><li><strong>The most common causes of vertigo symptoms in primary care </strong>are benign paroxysmal positional vertigo, Meniere's disease, and vestibular neuronitis [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vertigo/references/\">Dommaraju and Perera, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vertigo/references/\">BMJ Best Practice, 2017</a>].  <ul><li>In a prospective study in primary care of 70 people with vertigo [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vertigo/references/\">Hanley and O'Dowd, 2002</a>] 42% had benign paroxysmal positional vertigo; 41% had vestibular neuronitis; 10% had Meniere's disease; and the remainder had stroke, transient ischaemic attack, multiple sclerosis, or psychogenic vertigo. However, these findings may be misleading as:<ul><li>It is unclear whether they were working diagnoses before further investigation or confirmed diagnoses.</li><li>CKS expert reviewers highlighted that the study overestimated the incidence of Meniere's disease (which is rare) and omits migrainous vertigo (which may be one of the most common causes of vertigo).</li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field ff29e175-6e8b-4cee-ba86-262d52d45901 --><!-- end item b9e1a3e3-35f4-4aea-932c-1189078c9fbf -->","topic":{"id":"b94ca2c5-94f9-5b0b-8947-d7ed33aa5095","topicId":"d75cb8e1-a405-4add-9416-f4ddd4be71a4","topicName":"Vertigo","slug":"vertigo","lastRevised":"Last revised in November 2020","chapters":[{"id":"7cfbf245-8080-5408-b5af-46e6b015eaac","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"eb7fafc8-c3da-5207-80f3-b71728b95977","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"1a3b8a24-9e4d-5ef6-8305-9df3b1c317f2","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"a6c0480e-9ea3-560b-9ef9-010e2b6d6bc3","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Cha